Partial<T>

`Partial<T>` constructs a type with all properties of `T` set to optional.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

type PartialUser = Partial<User>;
// { name?: string; age?: number; email?: string }

function updateUser(id: number, updates: Partial<User>): void {
  // updates can have any subset of User properties
  console.log(`Updating user ${id}:`, updates);
}

updateUser(1, { name: "Alice" });
updateUser(1, { age: 31, email: "alice@example.com" });
updateUser(1, {}); // Empty object is also valid
```

### How It Works

```typescript
// Built-in definition:
type Partial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P];
};
```

### Practical Use Cases

- API PATCH requests (partial updates)
- Form state where fields are gradually filled
- Configuration with defaults
- Builder pattern stages

### Deep Partial

```typescript
type DeepPartial<T> = {
  [P in keyof T]?: T[P] extends object ? DeepPartial<T[P]> : T[P];
};

interface Config {
  server: { host: string; port: number };
  auth: { key: string; secret: string };
}

type DeepPartialConfig = DeepPartial<Config>;
// { server?: { host?: string; port?: number }; auth?: { key?: string; secret?: string } }
```

> **Key Point:** `Partial` is ideal for making all properties optional in update operations.

codeExample:
interface Product {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  price: number;
  description: string;
  category: string;
  inStock: boolean;
}

class ProductService {
  updateProduct(id: number, changes: Partial<Product>): Product {
    // Partial allows us to update only specific fields
    console.log(`Updating product ${id} with:`, changes);
    return { id, name: "", price: 0, description: "", category: "", inStock: false, ...changes };
  }

  validateProduct(product: Partial<Product>): boolean {
    if (product.price !== undefined && product.price < 0) {
      return false;
    }
    return true;
  }
}
